    "sections": [
      {
        "heading": "What It Is",
        "content": "The only honest way to backtest a predictive model on time-series data. Train on a window of past data, predict on the next unseen period, slide the window forward, repeat. Simulates how the model would have performed if deployed in real time."
      },
      {
        "heading": "Why It Matters",
        "content": "Standard train/test splits (or k-fold cross-validation) **leak future information** in time-series data. A model trained on Jan-Dec and tested on random samples from that range has \"seen\" data that follows its test points — this is **lookahead bias**, the #1 sin in quantitative finance."
      },
      {
        "heading": "How It Works",
        "content": "```\nTime ───────────────────────────────────────────>\n\nFold 1: [====TRAIN====][TEST]\nFold 2:    [====TRAIN====][TEST]\nFold 3:       [====TRAIN====][TEST]\n...\nFold N:                      [====TRAIN====][TEST]\n\nEach fold:\n1. Train model on [train_window] hours of historical data\n2. Predict the next [step] hours (e.g., 24h)\n3. Record prediction vs actual outcome\n4. Slide window forward by [step]\n5. Retrain every [retrain] steps (e.g., weekly)\n```"
      },
      {
        "heading": "Signal Forge Implementation",
        "content": "```python\n# backtest.py — WalkForwardBacktester\ntrain_window = 720   # 30 days of hourly data\nstep = 24            # predict daily\nretrain = 7          # retrain model every 7 steps (weekly)\n\n# Result: 303 folds for BTC, 3,236 for altcoins (pooled across 10 coins)\n```"
      },
      {
        "heading": "Key Concepts",
        "content": "- **Expanding window**: train set grows over time (uses all history). Better for regime detection.\n- **Rolling window**: train set stays fixed size (drops old data). Better if market dynamics change.\n- Signal Forge uses rolling (fixed 720h window) — crypto markets change fast.\n- **Purged cross-validation**: leaves a gap between train and test to prevent data leakage from overlapping targets."
      },
      {
        "heading": "Metrics to Track Per Fold",
        "content": "| Metric | What it tells you |\n|--------|-------------------|\n| Accuracy | % of correct direction predictions |\n| Precision | When model says \"up,\" how often is it right? |\n| Quant - Sharpe Ratio | Risk-adjusted return of following the signals |\n| Quant - Maximum Drawdown | Worst peak-to-trough loss |"
      },
      {
        "heading": "Gotchas",
        "content": "- Need enough data: train_window + step = minimum rows per fold (Signal Forge: 744 hours minimum)\n- Retraining frequency matters: too often = overfitting to noise, too rarely = stale model\n- Always compare against ML - Baseline Models — beating 50% means nothing if always_up gets 53%"
      },
      {
        "heading": "Research Next Steps",
        "content": "- [ ] Read Lopez de Prado: \"Advances in Financial Machine Learning\" Ch. 7 (cross-validation in finance)\n- [ ] Implement purged k-fold as alternative to rolling window\n- [ ] Test expanding window vs rolling window on Signal Forge data\n- [ ] Analyze if edge decays over time (early folds vs late folds)"
      }
    ],
